```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;
    server_name example.com www.example.com;

    root /var/www/example.com/html;
    index index.html index.htm;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
    }
}
```
**server** block defines a virtual host. Nginx selects the server based on `listen` address/port and `server_name`. Use `default_server` for fallback.

```nginx
upstream backend {
    least_conn;                       # or ip_hash; or hash $uri;
    server 10.0.0.1:8080 weight=3;   # 3x traffic
    server 10.0.0.2:8080;            # default weight=1
    server 10.0.0.3:8080 backup;     # only when others fail
    server 10.0.0.4:8080 down;       # marked offline
    server 10.0.0.5:8080 max_fails=3 fail_timeout=30s;

    keepalive 32;  # connection pool to backends
}
```
**upstream** defines load-balanced backends. Methods: `round-robin` (default), `least_conn`, `ip_hash` (sticky), `hash` (custom key). `weight` controls distribution.

```nginx
# Simple proxy:
location /api/ {
    proxy_pass http://backend:3000;    # keeps /api/ prefix
}

# Strip prefix:
location /api/ {
    proxy_pass http://backend:3000/;   # trailing / strips /api/
}

# To upstream group:
location / {
    proxy_pass http://my_upstream;
}

# Essential headers:
proxy_set_header Host              $host;
proxy_set_header X-Real-IP         $remote_addr;
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For   $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
```
**proxy_pass** forwards requests to backend servers. Trailing `/` in URL controls whether the location prefix is stripped. Always set forwarding headers.

```nginx
# Modern SSL configuration (A+ rating):
ssl_certificate     /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/fullchain.pem;
ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/privkey.pem;

ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256;
ssl_prefer_server_ciphers off;

ssl_session_cache shared:SSL:10m;
ssl_session_timeout 1d;
ssl_session_tickets off;

ssl_stapling on;
ssl_stapling_verify on;
```
**SSL/TLS** configuration. Use Let's Encrypt with `certbot --nginx`. Test with `ssllabs.com`. Only enable TLSv1.2+ for modern security.

```nginx
# Static site:
location / {
    try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
}

# SPA (React/Vue/Angular):
location / {
    try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
}

# PHP (Laravel/WordPress):
location / {
    try_files $uri $uri/ /index.php?$query_string;
}

# Named location fallback:
location / {
    try_files $uri @backend;
}
location @backend {
    proxy_pass http://app:3000;
}
```
**try_files** checks file existence in order. The last argument is the fallback (URI or error code). Essential for SPA routing and PHP frameworks.

```nginx
gzip on;
gzip_vary on;
gzip_proxied any;
gzip_comp_level 6;
gzip_min_length 256;
gzip_types
    text/plain
    text/css
    text/javascript
    application/javascript
    application/json
    application/xml
    image/svg+xml
    font/woff2;
```
**gzip** compression reduces response size by 60-80%. Level 4-6 is the sweet spot. Don't compress images (already compressed) or responses under 256 bytes. `gzip_vary` is essential for CDN caching.

```nginx
# Define zone in http block:
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=api:10m rate=10r/s;
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=login:10m rate=1r/s;

# Apply in location:
location /api/ {
    limit_req zone=api burst=20 nodelay;
    limit_req_status 429;
}

location /login {
    limit_req zone=login burst=5;
}
```
**Rate limiting** uses leaky bucket algorithm. `rate=10r/s` allows 10 req/sec. `burst=20` buffers 20 extra. `nodelay` processes burst immediately instead of queuing.

```nginx
# Prevent clickjacking:
add_header X-Frame-Options "SAMEORIGIN" always;

# Prevent MIME sniffing:
add_header X-Content-Type-Options "nosniff" always;

# Force HTTPS:
add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload" always;

# Content Security Policy:
add_header Content-Security-Policy "default-src 'self'" always;

# Referrer policy:
add_header Referrer-Policy "strict-origin-when-cross-origin" always;

# Permissions policy:
add_header Permissions-Policy "camera=(), microphone=()" always;
```
**Security headers** protect against common web attacks. Use `always` to send on error pages too. Test at securityheaders.com.

```nginx
# Permanent redirect (301):
rewrite ^/old/(.*)$ /new/$1 permanent;

# Temporary redirect (302):
rewrite ^/temp/(.*)$ /alt/$1 redirect;

# Internal rewrite (invisible to client):
rewrite ^/api/v1/(.*)$ /api/v2/$1 last;

# Stop processing:
rewrite ^/done/(.*)$ /$1 break;

# Prefer return for simple redirects:
return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
```
**rewrite** transforms URIs with regex. `last` restarts location matching. `break` stops rewrite processing. For simple redirects, `return` is faster than `rewrite`.

```nginx
location /ws/ {
    proxy_pass http://backend:8080;
    proxy_http_version 1.1;
    proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
    proxy_set_header Connection "upgrade";
    proxy_set_header Host $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;

    # Long timeouts for persistent connections:
    proxy_read_timeout 86400s;
    proxy_send_timeout 86400s;
}
```
**WebSocket** proxying requires HTTP/1.1, Upgrade and Connection headers. Set long timeouts (86400s = 24h) to prevent idle disconnection.

```nginx
# Map User-Agent to mobile flag:
map $http_user_agent $is_mobile {
    default        0;
    ~*mobile       1;
    ~*android      1;
    ~*iphone       1;
}

# Map URI to backend:
map $uri $backend {
    default         http://app:3000;
    ~^/api/         http://api:8080;
    ~^/admin/       http://admin:9090;
}

# Use in config:
if ($is_mobile) {
    rewrite ^ /mobile$uri last;
}
```
**map** creates variables based on other variables. Evaluated lazily (only when used). More efficient than multiple if statements.

```nginx
# PHP-FPM via Unix socket (recommended):
location ~ \.php$ {
    include fastcgi_params;
    fastcgi_pass unix:/run/php/php8.2-fpm.sock;
    fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
    fastcgi_index index.php;
    fastcgi_intercept_errors on;
    fastcgi_buffer_size 16k;
    fastcgi_buffers 4 16k;
}

# PHP-FPM via TCP (for separate server):
location ~ \.php$ {
    fastcgi_pass 10.0.0.5:9000;
    # ...
}
```
**FastCGI** connects nginx to PHP-FPM, Python (via flup), or other FastCGI apps. Unix sockets are faster for same-server setups. TCP for remote.

```nginx
# Standard combined log:
access_log /var/log/nginx/access.log;

# JSON log for ELK/Grafana:
log_format json escape=json
    '{"time":"$time_iso8601",'
    '"ip":"$remote_addr",'
    '"method":"$request_method",'
    '"uri":"$uri",'
    '"status":$status,'
    '"size":$body_bytes_sent,'
    '"time_ms":$request_time,'
    '"upstream_ms":"$upstream_response_time"}';
access_log /var/log/nginx/access.json json;

# Conditional logging (skip health checks):
map $uri $loggable {
    /health  0;
    default  1;
}
access_log /var/log/nginx/access.log combined if=$loggable;

# Disable for static assets:
location ~* \.(css|js|png|jpg)$ {
    access_log off;
}
```
**Logging** - JSON format integrates with ELK/Grafana Loki. Use conditional logging to reduce noise. `$request_time` measures total request processing time.

```nginx
# Worker tuning:
worker_processes auto;          # = CPU cores
worker_rlimit_nofile 65535;     # max open files per worker

events {
    worker_connections 4096;     # connections per worker
    multi_accept on;             # accept all new connections
    use epoll;                   # Linux: epoll, FreeBSD: kqueue
}

# TCP optimization:
sendfile on;        # zero-copy file serving
tcp_nopush on;      # combine headers + data
tcp_nodelay on;     # disable Nagle's algorithm

# Keepalive:
keepalive_timeout 65;
keepalive_requests 1000;

# Buffer sizes:
client_body_buffer_size   16k;
client_header_buffer_size 1k;
large_client_header_buffers 4 16k;

# File caching:
open_file_cache max=1000 inactive=20s;
open_file_cache_valid 30s;
open_file_cache_min_uses 2;
```
**Performance tuning** - match workers to CPUs, tune connections to expected load, enable sendfile for static content. Monitor with `stub_status` module.

```nginx
# Enable status page (restrict access!):
location /nginx_status {
    stub_status on;
    allow 127.0.0.1;
    allow 10.0.0.0/8;
    deny all;
}

# Output:
# Active connections: 291
# server accepts handled requests
#  16630948 16630948 31070465
# Reading: 6 Writing: 179 Waiting: 106
```
**stub_status** provides basic metrics. Active connections = reading + writing + waiting. Use for monitoring with Prometheus (via nginx-exporter) or Datadog.

hovers.if_directive:
## if directive

```nginx
if (condition) { ... }
```

**Warning: "If is Evil" in Nginx.** The `if` directive in location context can cause unexpected behaviors.

**Safe uses (inside server context):**
```nginx
# Redirect based on host
if ($host = 'old.example.com') {
    return 301 https://new.example.com$request_uri;
}

# Block by method
if ($request_method !~ ^(GET|POST)$) {
    return 405;
}
```

**Dangerous (inside location):**
```nginx
# DON'T: if + proxy_pass is unpredictable
location / {
    if ($arg_cache = "no") {
        proxy_pass http://nocache;  # UNRELIABLE
    }
}
```

**Safe alternatives:**
- Use `map` for variable mapping
- Use `try_files` for file existence checks
- Use multiple `location` blocks instead
- Use `return` and `rewrite` (only safe directives inside `if`)

**Only these directives are safe inside `if` in a location:**
`return`, `rewrite`, `set`

hovers.proxy_cache:
## proxy_cache

```nginx
proxy_cache zone;
proxy_cache_path path levels= keys_zone= ...;
```

Configure response caching from proxied servers.

**Setup:**
```nginx
http {
    # Define cache zone (10m metadata, 1g max size)
    proxy_cache_path /var/cache/nginx levels=1:2
        keys_zone=my_cache:10m max_size=1g
        inactive=60m use_temp_path=off;

    server {
        location / {
            proxy_cache my_cache;
            proxy_cache_valid 200 302 10m;
            proxy_cache_valid 404 1m;
            proxy_cache_key $scheme$request_method$host$request_uri;
            proxy_cache_bypass $http_cache_control;

            # Add cache status header
            add_header X-Cache-Status $upstream_cache_status;

            proxy_pass http://backend;
        }
    }
}
```

**Cache status values** (`$upstream_cache_status`):
- `MISS` — not in cache, fetched from upstream
- `HIT` — served from cache
- `EXPIRED` — cache entry expired, refreshed from upstream
- `BYPASS` — cache bypassed due to `proxy_cache_bypass`
- `STALE` — serving stale entry (upstream error + `proxy_cache_use_stale`)

**Tip:** Use `proxy_cache_use_stale` for resilience:
```nginx
proxy_cache_use_stale error timeout http_500 http_502 http_503 http_504;
```

hovers.error_page:
## error_page

```nginx
error_page code ... [=[response]] uri;
```

Define custom error pages or internal redirects for specific HTTP status codes.

```nginx
# Simple custom error pages
error_page 404 /404.html;
error_page 500 502 503 504 /50x.html;

# Change response code
error_page 404 =200 /index.html;  # SPA fallback

# Internal redirect to named location
error_page 404 @fallback;
location @fallback {
    proxy_pass http://backend;
}

# Use internal redirect
location /404.html {
    internal;  # prevent direct access
    root /var/www/errors;
}
```

**Tip:** Combine with `try_files` for cleaner flow:
```nginx
try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
error_page 404 /custom_404.html;
```

hovers.auth_basic:
## auth_basic

```nginx
auth_basic string | off;
auth_basic_user_file file;
```

HTTP Basic Authentication using username/password file.

```nginx
location /admin {
    auth_basic "Admin Area";
    auth_basic_user_file /etc/nginx/.htpasswd;
}

# Disable auth for sub-location
location /admin/public {
    auth_basic off;
}
```

**Create password file:**
```bash
# Using htpasswd (Apache utils)
sudo htpasswd -c /etc/nginx/.htpasswd user1

# Or with openssl
echo "user1:$(openssl passwd -apr1 'password')" >> /etc/nginx/.htpasswd
```

**Tip:** For modern apps, prefer `auth_request` with an external auth service over basic auth.

hovers.allow_deny:
## allow / deny

```nginx
allow address | CIDR | unix: | all;
deny address | CIDR | unix: | all;
```

IP-based access control. Rules are checked in order — first match wins.

```nginx
# Restrict to internal IPs
location /admin {
    allow 192.168.1.0/24;
    allow 10.0.0.0/8;
    deny all;
}

# Block specific IPs
location / {
    deny 1.2.3.4;
    deny 5.6.7.0/24;
    allow all;
}

# Combine with auth
location /internal {
    satisfy any;  # allow OR auth (default: all = AND)
    allow 192.168.0.0/16;
    deny all;
    auth_basic "Restricted";
    auth_basic_user_file /etc/nginx/.htpasswd;
}
```

**Tip:** Use `satisfy any` when you want either IP match or authentication (not both).

hovers.expires:
## expires

```nginx
expires [modified] time;
expires epoch | max | off;
```

Control browser caching via `Expires` and `Cache-Control` headers.

```nginx
# Static assets — long cache
location ~* \.(jpg|jpeg|png|gif|ico|css|js|woff2)$ {
    expires 1y;
    add_header Cache-Control "public, immutable";
}

# HTML — short cache
location ~* \.html$ {
    expires 1h;
}

# API — no cache
location /api {
    expires -1;  # Cache-Control: no-cache
    # or
    expires off;  # don't modify headers
}

# Special values
expires epoch;  # Cache-Control: no-cache (Expires: Jan 1 1970)
expires max;    # Expires: Dec 31 2037
```

hovers.auth_request:
## auth_request

```nginx
auth_request uri | off;
auth_request_set $variable value;
```

Subrequest-based authentication — delegates auth to an external service.

```nginx
server {
    location /protected/ {
        auth_request /auth;
        auth_request_set $auth_user $upstream_http_x_user;
        proxy_set_header X-User $auth_user;
        proxy_pass http://backend;
    }

    location = /auth {
        internal;  # only accessible via internal subrequest
        proxy_pass http://auth-service/verify;
        proxy_pass_request_body off;
        proxy_set_header Content-Length "";
        proxy_set_header X-Original-URI $request_uri;
        proxy_set_header X-Original-Method $request_method;
    }

    # Handle auth failures
    error_page 401 = @login_redirect;
    location @login_redirect {
        return 302 /login?next=$request_uri;
    }
}
```

**How it works:**
1. Nginx sends subrequest to `/auth` before processing
2. If auth returns **2xx** → request proceeds
3. If auth returns **401/403** → access denied
4. Use `auth_request_set` to pass data from auth response

hovers.real_ip:
## real_ip_header / set_real_ip_from

Extract real client IP when nginx is behind a proxy, CDN, or load balancer.

```nginx
# Behind Cloudflare
set_real_ip_from 173.245.48.0/20;
set_real_ip_from 103.21.244.0/22;
set_real_ip_from 103.22.200.0/22;
# ... (full Cloudflare IP list)
real_ip_header CF-Connecting-IP;

# Behind AWS ALB/ELB
set_real_ip_from 10.0.0.0/8;
real_ip_header X-Forwarded-For;
real_ip_recursive on;  # skip known proxy IPs in chain

# Behind generic reverse proxy
set_real_ip_from 192.168.0.0/16;
set_real_ip_from 172.16.0.0/12;
real_ip_header X-Real-IP;
```

**Important:** `real_ip_recursive on` makes nginx traverse `X-Forwarded-For` from right to left, skipping trusted addresses, to find the real client IP.

**Requires:** `ngx_http_realip_module` (included in most packages).

hovers.stream:
## stream (TCP/UDP proxy)

```nginx
stream { ... }
```

TCP/UDP load balancing and proxying (non-HTTP protocols).

```nginx
stream {
    # MySQL load balancing
    upstream mysql_backend {
        server 10.0.0.1:3306 weight=5;
        server 10.0.0.2:3306;
    }
    server {
        listen 3306;
        proxy_pass mysql_backend;
        proxy_connect_timeout 1s;
    }

    # Redis proxy with SSL termination  
    server {
        listen 6380 ssl;
        ssl_certificate /etc/ssl/cert.pem;
        ssl_certificate_key /etc/ssl/key.pem;
        proxy_pass 127.0.0.1:6379;
    }

    # UDP DNS proxy
    server {
        listen 53 udp;
        proxy_pass dns_upstream;
    }
    upstream dns_upstream {
        server 8.8.8.8:53;
        server 8.8.4.4:53;
    }
}
```

**Note:** `stream` block is at the same level as `http` block, not inside it.

contents.value:
```nginx
proxy_pass http://backend?$args;
# same as $query_string
if ($args ~* "debug=true") {
    # conditional logic
}
```
**$args** contains the full query string from the request URL (everything after `?`). Alias for `$query_string`. Not decoded.

```nginx
limit_conn_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=addr:10m;
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=req:10m rate=10r/s;
```
**$binary_remote_addr** is the client IP in binary form (4 bytes for IPv4, 16 for IPv6). More memory-efficient than `$remote_addr` for shared memory zones like `limit_conn_zone` and `limit_req_zone`.

```nginx
fastcgi_param DOCUMENT_ROOT $document_root;
fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
```
**$document_root** returns the value of `root` or `alias` for the current request. Commonly used with FastCGI to pass the document root to backend applications.

```nginx
fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
fastcgi_param SCRIPT_NAME $fastcgi_script_name;
```
**$fastcgi_script_name** contains the request URI or, if a URI ends with `/`, the URI plus `index` filename set by `fastcgi_index`. Used to build `SCRIPT_FILENAME` for PHP-FPM.

```nginx
proxy_set_header Host $host;
if ($host = 'old.example.com') {
    return 301 https://new.example.com$request_uri;
}
```
**$host** is the hostname from the request line, or the `Host` header, or the server name matching the request (in that priority). Lowercase and without port. The most common way to reference the requested hostname.

```nginx
if ($http_referer ~* "spam\.com") {
    return 403;
}
log_format combined '... "$http_referer" ...';
```
**$http_referer** contains the value of the `Referer` request header. Used for hotlink protection, logging, and conditional access control.

```nginx
proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
proxy_set_header Connection "upgrade";
# WebSocket proxying
map $http_upgrade $connection_upgrade {
    default upgrade;
    ''      close;
}
```
**$http_upgrade** holds the `Upgrade` request header value. Essential for WebSocket proxying — Nginx uses it to detect upgrade requests and forward them to backend servers.

```nginx
if ($http_user_agent ~* "(bot|crawl|spider)") {
    return 403;
}
log_format main '... "$http_user_agent"';
```
**$http_user_agent** contains the `User-Agent` request header. Used for bot detection, browser-specific rules, and access logging.

```nginx
if ($query_string ~* "utm_") {
    # handle tracking params
}
proxy_pass http://backend?$query_string;
```
**$query_string** is the full query string of the request (same as `$args`). Contains everything after `?` in the URL, not URL-decoded.

```nginx
allow 192.168.1.0/24;
deny all;
log_format main '$remote_addr - $remote_user [$time_local]...';
proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
```
**$remote_addr** is the client's IP address. When behind a load balancer, this shows the LB's IP — use `real_ip_header` and `set_real_ip_from` to extract the real client IP.

```nginx
if ($request_method = POST) {
    return 405;
}
limit_except GET POST {
    deny all;
}
```
**$request_method** contains the HTTP method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.). Used in conditionals and access control.

```nginx
return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
proxy_pass http://backend$request_uri;
```
**$request_uri** is the full original request URI including the query string, as sent by the client. Not modified by internal rewrites. Use `$uri` for the normalized/rewritten URI.

```nginx
if ($scheme = http) {
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
```
**$scheme** is the request scheme — `http` or `https`. Commonly used for HTTPS redirect and to pass protocol info to backends via `X-Forwarded-Proto`.

```nginx
add_header X-Served-By $server_name;
log_format vhost '$server_name $remote_addr ...';
```
**$server_name** is the name of the server block that handled the request, from the `server_name` directive. Useful in logging and response headers for debugging multi-vhost setups.

```nginx
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Port $server_port;
if ($server_port = 8080) { ... }
```
**$server_port** is the port of the server that accepted the request. Useful for port-based routing logic and forwarding port info to backend applications.

```nginx
log_format main '... $status $body_bytes_sent ...';
if ($status = 404) {
    access_log /var/log/nginx/404.log;
}
```
**$status** is the HTTP response status code. Available in log format and post-processing. Note: not available in all contexts during request processing.

```nginx
add_header X-Cache-Status $upstream_cache_status;
log_format cache '... $upstream_cache_status ...';
# Values: MISS, HIT, EXPIRED, STALE, UPDATING, REVALIDATED, BYPASS
```
**$upstream_cache_status** indicates the cache status of the response. Returned values: `HIT` (served from cache), `MISS` (fetched from upstream), `EXPIRED`, `STALE`, `BYPASS`, `REVALIDATED`, `UPDATING`.

```nginx
http {
    include       mime.types;
    default_type  application/octet-stream;
    sendfile      on;
    keepalive_timeout 65;

    server { ... }
}
```
**http** is the top-level configuration block for all HTTP/HTTPS traffic. Contains `server` blocks, `upstream` definitions, and global HTTP settings like logging, gzip, and connection timeouts.

```nginx
events {
    worker_connections 1024;
    multi_accept on;
    use epoll;  # Linux
}
```
**events** block configures the connection processing model. Sets maximum concurrent connections per worker (`worker_connections`), enables accepting multiple connections at once (`multi_accept`), and selects the event method (`epoll`, `kqueue`).

```nginx
include /etc/nginx/mime.types;
include /etc/nginx/conf.d/*.conf;
include /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/*;
include snippets/ssl-params.conf;
```
**include** imports another configuration file or files matching a glob pattern. Supports wildcards. Used to organize configs into modular files. Paths are relative to the main config directory unless absolute.

```nginx
events {
    worker_connections 1024;
}
# Max connections = worker_processes × worker_connections
```
**worker_connections** sets the maximum number of simultaneous connections each worker process can handle. Includes both client connections and upstream connections. Total capacity = workers × connections.

```nginx
events {
    multi_accept on;
}
```
**multi_accept** allows a worker process to accept multiple new connections at once instead of one at a time. Improves performance under high connection rates. Default: `off`.

```nginx
sendfile on;
sendfile_max_chunk 1m;
```
**sendfile** enables the `sendfile()` system call for serving static files, which bypasses user-space buffering by transferring data directly between file descriptors in the kernel. Significantly improves static file serving performance.

```nginx
sendfile on;
tcp_nopush on;
```
**tcp_nopush** enables `TCP_CORK` (Linux) or `TCP_NOPUSH` (BSD). Optimizes static file delivery by sending HTTP headers and file contents in a single packet. Only works when `sendfile` is enabled.

```nginx
default_type application/octet-stream;
default_type text/plain;
```
**default_type** sets the MIME type for responses when the type cannot be determined from the file extension via the `types` block. `application/octet-stream` triggers download; `text/plain` shows as text.

```nginx
types {
    text/html  html htm;
    text/css   css;
    application/javascript js;
    image/png  png;
}
# Usually loaded via: include mime.types;
```
**types** maps file extensions to MIME types. Typically loaded from the `mime.types` file using `include`. Custom types can be added for specific file extensions.

```nginx
server {
    root /var/www/html;
    location /images/ {
        root /data;  # serves from /data/images/
    }
}
```
**root** sets the document root directory for requests. The full path is constructed by appending the URI to `root`. Unlike `alias`, the location prefix is included in the filesystem path.

```nginx
location /static/ {
    alias /var/www/assets/;  # /static/img.png → /var/www/assets/img.png
}
# versus root:
location /static/ {
    root /var/www;  # /static/img.png → /var/www/static/img.png
}
```
**alias** replaces the location prefix with the specified path. Unlike `root`, the location prefix is stripped. Must end with `/` when the location ends with `/`.

```nginx
set $backend http://localhost:8080;
set $limit_key $binary_remote_addr;
if ($http_x_custom) {
    set $backend http://localhost:9090;
}
proxy_pass $backend;
```
**set** assigns a value to a variable. Variables can be used throughout the configuration for dynamic routing, header values, and conditional logic. Variables are evaluated lazily per-request.

```nginx
if ($request_method = POST) { return 405; }
if ($http_user_agent ~* "bot") { return 403; }
if ($scheme = http) {
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}
# Operators: =, !=, ~, ~*, !~, !~*, -f, -d, -e, -x
```
**if** evaluates a condition and applies the enclosed directives. Supports string comparison (`=`, `!=`), regex (`~`, `~*`), and file tests (`-f`, `-d`, `-e`). **Warning**: `if` inside `location` has known issues — prefer `map` or `try_files` when possible.

```nginx
error_log /var/log/nginx/error.log warn;
error_log /var/log/nginx/debug.log debug;
error_log syslog:server=192.168.1.1 info;
# Levels: debug, info, notice, warn, error, crit, alert, emerg
```
**error_log** configures the error log file and minimum severity level. Can be set at `main`, `http`, `server`, or `location` level. Multiple `error_log` directives can be used for different log levels.

```nginx
access_log /var/log/nginx/access.log main;
access_log /var/log/nginx/json.log json_format buffer=32k flush=5s;
access_log off;  # disable
```
**access_log** configures the access log file, format, and optional buffering. Reference a `log_format` by name. Supports buffered writes for performance. Use `off` to disable logging for specific locations.

```nginx
location /internal-api/ {
    internal;  # only accessible via internal redirects
    proxy_pass http://backend;
}
error_page 404 /404.html;
location = /404.html {
    internal;
}
```
**internal** marks a location as only accessible through internal requests (e.g., `error_page`, `try_files`, `X-Accel-Redirect`). Direct client requests to an internal location return `404`.

```nginx
proxy_set_header Host $host;
proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
```
**proxy_set_header** sets or overrides request headers sent to the proxied server. Essential for passing client IP, hostname, and protocol information to backends. Inherited from outer blocks but reset if any are set in the current block.

```nginx
proxy_cache_path /var/cache/nginx levels=1:2
    keys_zone=my_cache:10m
    max_size=10g
    inactive=60m
    use_temp_path=off;

server {
    location / {
        proxy_cache my_cache;
        proxy_pass http://backend;
    }
}
```
**proxy_cache_path** defines a disk cache zone. `keys_zone` sets the shared memory zone for keys; `max_size` limits disk usage; `inactive` sets how long unused items are kept; `levels` sets the directory hierarchy depth.

```nginx
proxy_cache_bypass $http_cache_control $cookie_nocache;
proxy_cache_bypass $arg_nocache;
```
**proxy_cache_bypass** defines conditions to bypass the cache and fetch from upstream. If any listed variable is non-empty and not `0`, the cache is bypassed. The response may still be cached for future requests.

```nginx
proxy_next_upstream error timeout http_502 http_503;
proxy_next_upstream_tries 3;
proxy_next_upstream_timeout 10s;
```
**proxy_next_upstream** defines conditions under which a request is passed to the next upstream server. Enables automatic failover in load-balanced setups. Use with `upstream` blocks.

```nginx
proxy_redirect off;
proxy_redirect http://backend/ /;
proxy_redirect default;
```
**proxy_redirect** rewrites the `Location` and `Refresh` headers in upstream responses. `default` replaces the upstream URL with the location; `off` disables rewriting. Needed when backends send absolute redirect URLs that don't match the public URL.

```nginx
proxy_cookie_domain backend.internal example.com;
proxy_cookie_domain ~\.internal$ .example.com;
```
**proxy_cookie_domain** rewrites the `domain` attribute of `Set-Cookie` headers from the upstream server. Essential when the backend uses internal hostnames that differ from the public domain.

```nginx
proxy_cookie_path /api/ /;
proxy_cookie_path ~*^/internal /;
```
**proxy_cookie_path** rewrites the `path` attribute of `Set-Cookie` headers from upstream. Needed when the backend sets cookie paths that differ from the public URL structure.

```nginx
add_header X-Frame-Options "SAMEORIGIN" always;
add_header X-Content-Type-Options "nosniff" always;
add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000" always;
add_header Cache-Control "public, max-age=3600";
```
**add_header** adds a response header. Use `always` to include the header in error responses too (4xx/5xx). Headers are inherited from outer blocks only if no `add_header` directives exist in the current block.

```nginx
ssl_stapling on;
ssl_stapling_verify on;
resolver 8.8.8.8 8.8.4.4 valid=300s;
```
**ssl_stapling** enables OCSP stapling — Nginx fetches and caches the OCSP response and sends it during the TLS handshake. Improves client connection speed by avoiding separate OCSP queries. Requires a `resolver`.

```nginx
ssl_stapling_verify on;
ssl_trusted_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/chain.pem;
```
**ssl_stapling_verify** enables verification of OCSP responses. Requires `ssl_trusted_certificate` pointing to the CA chain. Protects against forged OCSP responses.

```nginx
location /admin/ {
    allow 192.168.1.0/24;
    allow 10.0.0.0/8;
    deny all;
}
```
**allow** permits access from the specified IP address or CIDR range. Processed in order with `deny` directives — first match wins. Always end with `deny all` for whitelist-only access.

```nginx
location /admin/ {
    allow 192.168.1.0/24;
    deny all;  # block everyone else
}
deny 10.0.0.1;  # block specific IP
```
**deny** blocks access from the specified IP address or CIDR range. `deny all` blocks everyone. Processed in order with `allow` directives — first match wins. Returns `403 Forbidden`.

```nginx
location /admin/ {
    auth_basic "Admin Area";
    auth_basic_user_file /etc/nginx/.htpasswd;
}
# Create password file: htpasswd -c /etc/nginx/.htpasswd username
```
**auth_basic_user_file** specifies the file containing username:password pairs for HTTP Basic authentication. Generate with `htpasswd` from Apache utils. Pairs with `auth_basic` directive.

```nginx
location /protected/ {
    auth_request /auth;
    auth_request_set $auth_user $upstream_http_x_auth_user;
    proxy_set_header X-Auth-User $auth_user;
    proxy_pass http://backend;
}
```
**auth_request_set** captures values from the auth subrequest response into variables. Commonly extracts user info, roles, or tokens from auth service headers for forwarding to the backend.

```nginx
sub_filter 'http://backend' 'https://example.com';
sub_filter_once off;  # replace all occurrences
sub_filter_types text/html text/css;
```
**sub_filter** performs string replacement in the response body. Useful for fixing URLs, injecting scripts, or modifying upstream responses without changing the backend. Use `sub_filter_once off` for global replacement.

```nginx
http {
    limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=api:10m rate=10r/s;
}
server {
    location /api/ {
        limit_req zone=api burst=20 nodelay;
    }
}
```
**limit_req_zone** defines a shared memory zone for request rate limiting. Key (typically `$binary_remote_addr`) identifies clients; `rate` sets requests per second/minute. Zone size determines how many keys can be tracked.

```nginx
geo $allowed {
    default 0;
    192.168.1.0/24 1;
    10.0.0.0/8 1;
}
if ($allowed = 0) { return 403; }
```
**geo** creates a variable whose value depends on the client IP address. Matches against IP ranges/CIDRs. More efficient than multiple `if` conditions for IP-based routing or access control.

```nginx
set_real_ip_from 10.0.0.0/8;
real_ip_header X-Forwarded-For;
real_ip_header X-Real-IP;
real_ip_header proxy_protocol;
```
**real_ip_header** specifies the header to extract the real client IP from when Nginx is behind a proxy/load balancer. Common values: `X-Forwarded-For`, `X-Real-IP`, `proxy_protocol`. Requires `ngx_http_realip_module`.

```nginx
set_real_ip_from 10.0.0.0/8;
set_real_ip_from 172.16.0.0/12;
set_real_ip_from 192.168.0.0/16;
real_ip_header X-Forwarded-For;
```
**set_real_ip_from** defines trusted proxy addresses. Only `real_ip_header` values from these IPs are accepted. Prevents IP spoofing. List all load balancers, CDNs (e.g., Cloudflare ranges), and proxy IPs.

```nginx
location /files/ {
    autoindex on;
    autoindex_exact_size off;  # show human-readable sizes
    autoindex_localtime on;    # show local time
}
```
**autoindex** enables automatic directory listing when no index file is found. Shows files with sizes and modification dates. Default: `off`. Use with caution — may expose sensitive directory contents.

```nginx
open_file_cache max=1000 inactive=20s;
open_file_cache_valid 30s;
open_file_cache_min_uses 2;
```
**open_file_cache** caches file descriptors, sizes, modification times, and directory lookups. Reduces filesystem syscalls for frequently accessed files. `max` limits entries; `inactive` sets how long unused entries are kept.

```nginx
location ~ \.php$ {
    fastcgi_pass unix:/var/run/php/php-fpm.sock;
    fastcgi_pass 127.0.0.1:9000;
    fastcgi_index index.php;
    include fastcgi_params;
}
```
**fastcgi_pass** sets the address of a FastCGI server. Can be a Unix socket or TCP address. Primary directive for proxying requests to PHP-FPM and other FastCGI applications.

```nginx
fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
fastcgi_param QUERY_STRING $query_string;
fastcgi_param PHP_VALUE "error_log=/var/log/php_errors.log";
# Usually: include fastcgi_params;
```
**fastcgi_param** sets a parameter passed to the FastCGI server. `SCRIPT_FILENAME` is required for PHP-FPM. Standard parameters are typically loaded via `include fastcgi_params`. Custom PHP settings can be passed via `PHP_VALUE`.

```nginx
location / {
    uwsgi_pass unix:/tmp/uwsgi.sock;
    uwsgi_pass 127.0.0.1:8000;
    include uwsgi_params;
}
```
**uwsgi_pass** sets the address of a uWSGI server. Can be a Unix socket or TCP address. Primary directive for proxying to Python WSGI applications (Django, Flask) running under uWSGI.

```nginx
location /grpc.Service/ {
    grpc_pass grpc://127.0.0.1:50051;
    grpc_pass grpcs://backend;  # with TLS
}
```
**grpc_pass** proxies requests to a gRPC backend server. Use `grpc://` for plaintext or `grpcs://` for TLS backends. Requires `proxy_http_version 2` implicitly. Available since Nginx 1.13.10.

```nginx
mail {
    server_name mail.example.com;
    auth_http localhost:9000/auth;

    server {
        listen 993 ssl;
        protocol imap;
    }
    server {
        listen 587 ssl;
        protocol smtp;
        smtp_auth login plain;
    }
}
```
**mail** is the top-level block for configuring Nginx as a mail proxy (IMAP, POP3, SMTP). Requires `ngx_mail_module`. Supports authentication via HTTP backend and SSL/TLS.
